ircle></svg></button></div></div><div class=3D"comment-body"><p><span>What =
I found so clarifying is that reproductive strategy is coming from EVOLUTIO=
N, not from animals themselves, who are merely pawns of evolution. One of m=
y main complaints about evo psych was that it seemed to grant agency to ani=
mals that they do not have. Now I see that it's evolution itself that has a=
 kind of agency, in that its only goal is to produce more bodies. This make=
s sense to me, while I used to think evo psych claimed that animals sat aro=
und scheming about how best to produce more offspring. In fact, I don't thi=
nk any animals other than humans really care about reproducing; they just d=
o what nature compels them to do. We humans are also compelled to do many t=
hings, but we are clearly far more able to wrestle with evolutionary impuls=
es than other animals. If we weren't, there would be no birth control. And =
there wouldn't be so many men who pressure their girlfriends into getting a=
bortions (I saw a LOT of that when I volunteered at Planned Parenthood; evo=
lution might make a lot of men promiscuous, but it doesn't make these same =
men want to become fathers).</span></p><p><span>Anyway, thank you for anoth=
er fascinating piece! </span></p><div role=3D"button" class=3D"show-all-tog=
