 I was (much) younger and still in the dating pool I never understood why s=
ome really attractive, smart women seemed so attracted to really BAD men.</=
span></p><p><span>I got married at age 41 and have remained happily married=
 for almost 30 years and the idea of "dating" now seems loathsome.</span></=
p><p><span>I am a lawyer and was told I had no obvious deficits, other that=
 more than one woman I was attracted to told me I was "too nice to (serious=
ly date)." </span></p><p><span>Now that I can look on it from a place of be=
ing happily married, comfortable and without adolescent angst, I remain con=
founded. One example was when I was a sophomore at the Honors College of th=
e University of Oregon (50 years ago). I was dating an Alpha Chi Omega, whi=
ch was clearly the hottest sorority at the time at my university. Our relat=
ionship wasn't that serious, but what confounded me was his OTHER choice. I=
n what would turn out to be a catastrophically bad policy, the University o=
f Oregon welcomed a program called "Project Newgate" which placed active pr=
ison inmates into abandoned fraternity housing on campus. The "idea" was to=
 "normalize"  men convicted of rape and armed robbery by "integrating" them=
 into the general student population.</span></p><p><span>It was a disaster.=
 My one-time date, a really beautiful girl (about 19 at the time) who was v=
ery smart,  started dating a 35-year old rapist. Within 6 months she was in=
jecting heroin and methamphetamine, and thrown out of the University. </spa=
n></p><p><span>I spent the next 45 years as a trial prosecutor, handling ho=
micide and rape cases, and it never gave any special insight into the title=
 issue of Rob's post, "why (some) women are attracted to violent men?"</spa=
n></p><div role=3D"button" class=3D"show-all-toggle"><div class=3D"show-all=
